  "prompt": "How do I take input from STDIN in Python?",
  "response": "To take input from STDIN in Python, you can use the `input()` function. This function reads a line from input, which can be from the console or any other input stream, and returns it as a string.\n\nHere is a basic example of using `input()`:\n\n```python\n# Prompt the user for input\nuser_input = input(\"Please enter something: \")\n\n# Print the input received\nprint(\"You entered:\", user_input)\n```\n\nIf you are working with multiple pieces of input, you can call `input()` multiple times:\n\n```python\n# Take multiple inputs\nname = input(\"Enter your name: \")\nage = input(\"Enter your age: \")\n\n# Display the inputs\nprint(\"Your name is:\", name)\nprint(\"Your age is:\", age)\n```\n\nFor scenarios such as competitive programming or scripting where you need to handle multiple lines of input more efficiently, you may use `sys.stdin`. Here's how you can do that:\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\n# Read all lines from standard input\ninput_lines = sys.stdin.read().splitlines()\n\nfor line in input_lines:\n    print(\"You entered:\", line)\n```\n\nThis method can be particularly useful when reading input piped from files or other sources.\n\nIn competitive programming situations where input is often provided in bulk via standard input, `input()` might be slow and cumbersome. In such cases, you might use `sys.stdin.read` or `sys.stdin.readline`.\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\n# Read a single line from standard input\nsingle_line = sys.stdin.readline().strip()\n\n# Read all input from standard input\nall_input = sys.stdin.read().strip()\n\n# Read multiple lines from standard input\nlines = []\n while True:\n     line = sys.stdin.readline().strip()\n     if not line:\n         break\n       lines.append(line)\n       \n# Process the lines as needed\nfor line in lines:\n    print(\"You entered:\", line)\n```\n\nRemember that `sys.stdin.read()` will read until EOF, `sys.stdin.readline()` reads one line at a time, and `sys.stdin.read().splitlines()` reads all lines and splits them based on newline characters.\n\nThese methods are all adequate depending on your particular needs and should be chosen based on the volume and nature of your input.",
